GitHub Flow
Layman Explanation

Imagine a single main road where the final product lives.

Whenever you want to build something new:

Create a small side road (branch)

Work on it

Test it

Merge it back to the main road

That’s it. Very simple.

This workflow is used heavily on GitHub.

Diagram
main
  |
  |---- feature-login ---- merge ---->
  |
  |---- feature-payment -- merge ---->
  |
  |---- bug-fix --------- merge ---->

Workflow Steps

1️⃣ Create branch from main

git checkout -b feature-login


2️⃣ Work and commit.

3️⃣ Open Pull Request.

4️⃣ Review + testing.

5️⃣ Merge into main.

Interview Answer

GitHub Flow is a lightweight branching strategy where developers create short-lived feature branches from main, open pull requests for review, and merge changes back after testing.

Advantages

Very simple

Fast deployment

Works well with CI/CD

Ideal for web applications

Disadvantages

No structured release management

Hard to manage multiple production versions

